Virtual inheritance vs Regular inheritance

What is Virtual referring to?
	Inheritance. 

What is Public (private or protected) >
	Access Specifier.

Put them together:
a) 

Virtual Public B: 
This means that B is inherited virtually, 
ensuring that there is only one instance of B in the derived class hierarchy, 
even if multiple paths lead to B. 
This avoids ambiguity and reduces redundancy.

Public B: 
This means that B is inherited in a straight forward manner. 
If multiple paths lead to B, multiple instances of B could be created, 
which might lead to ambiguity or redundancy in the derived class hierarchy.

b)
public virtual and virtual public are functionally equivalent and can be used interchangeably. 
The ordering of public and virtual doesn’t change the meaning in this context.

